      "date": "2011-07-13 21:24:23.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified; I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\nPlease record the change not the bug: i.e.:\n\nLU-333: read_bytes in llite/*/stats *now* reports bytes read.\n\n... and necessary detail and why: i.e.:\n\nRemoved tallying of LLPROC_LL_[READ|WRITE]_BYTES from ./llite/vvp_io.c because ??. Tallying for LLPROC_LL_[READ|WRITE]_BYTES now performed in ./llite/file.c where the number of bytes read/written is readily available.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "f40594e7c4e05abdf1ce3e5b9cb66e20162edca8",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-07-13 21:44:01.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(2 inline comments)\n\nMinor cleanups to be done.\n\nIt would be a good idea to add a simple test to sanity.sh to zero the llite stats counter, write some data (say 65536 bytes, to match PAGE_SIZE for most clients), then use \"lctl get_param llite.*.stats\" to fetch the OST0 stats values and verify the read_bytes and write_bytes match.\n\nIt looks like sanity.sh test_127 is already doing this for the OSC, but it is using 2MB IO size.  Maybe test_127b should be written to do it for the llite stats in a similar manner.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
